The main outcomes of this project include:

(1) Enhancing and testing a polarimetric radar approach for retrieving mean shapes of ice cloud particles and snowflakes for applications with operational weather radar measurements;

(2) Studies of ice particle shape variability as a function of environmental parameters;

(3) Investigations of polarimetric radar variables at cloud radar frequencies;

(4) Developing and testing a dual-wavelength radar method to retrieve characteristic sizes of ice hydrometeors.



The outcome (1) allows for the use the operational National Weather Service (NWS) radar measurements to estimate mean shape of snowflakes which can lead to improvement of snowfall quantitative precipitation estimation (QPE). The outcome (2) provides insights on how hydrometeor shapes are impacted by different cloud microphysical process. It leads to better understanding of cold season precipitation formation mechanisms. The outcome (3) allows for the extension of QPE methods, which were originally developed for longer wavelength precipitation radars, to applications with higher frequency radars. The outcome (4) provides a dual-wavelength radar technique applicable to a number of ground-based and airborne radar systems for retrievals of characteristic sizes of ice hydrometeor distributions. Information on hydrometeor size is important for many applications ranging from assessing cloud feedback in climate models to refining QPE methods.



